/*
- (2) What we want to achieve with the dataset is simple. The goal is
      memory hardness, which is a property of functions that are hard
      to evaluate efficiently without a large amount of memory.

      - REMARK 1. This should act like a barrier, if you reduce the amount
        of memory that you use, performance should drop off drastically.

      This is pretty fitting for RandomX, as CPUs have access to memory
      controllers, so that means reading, writing and prefetching up to
      tens of gigabytes of DRAM.

- (3) Let's consider the two ASIC designs proposed by RandomX developers
      to try beat the CPU's slow external DRAM, so the goal is to somehow
      put the memory on-chip.

- (4)
- (5) An ASIC for fast mode mining at the time of RandomX's introduction
      would simply be not possible, as 2 GiBs of memory would be 
      economically infeasible to store on-chip. You would lose out of the 
      advantage of on chip memory, and would have to use external DRAM, 
      then at that point there is no advantage to a CPU.
*/
