/*
- (2) ... So, this ASIC will only store the cache, and execute the
      8 superscalarhash instances. Is that much slower?

- (3) Because the superscalarhash generator, which is a CPU simulator, 
      tries its hardest to maximise the dependency chain for all the 
      registers across the instructions so an ASIC can't just evaluate the 
      entire hash in parallel. Since each instruction depends on the 
      previous one maximally, OoO execution and the superscalar nature of 
      CPUs will be able to evaluate it efficiently. An ASIC would lose a 
      lot of efficiency on the performance front.

- (4) Also, it uses an incredible amount of power. Equivalent to just using
      external DRAM like a regular CPU.

- (5) No advantage over CPU, not in speed, or even in energy usage. Hence,
      this insentivises any ASIC to use external DRAM like CPUs. So 
      RandomX actually succeeds in being memory hard.

      REMARK 1: another slide section about saying yay memory hard!
*/
#slide(title: [(2.RX) Memory-Hardness])[
  Let's try a competitive light mode mining ASIC?
  
  #uncoverb(2)[
