/*
- (1) So, we are memory hard, but that's only for reading, so we're not
      taking advantage of the caches that exist in a CPU already.

- (2) Remember that CPUs have caches for frequently acccessed memory, and
      in basically all CPUs it's organised into an L1, L2, L3 hierarchy,
      with L1 being the closest to a core often being exclusively owned
      by a core, L2 being larger and slightly slower, holding data evicted
      by L1, and L3 being the largest and shared among most or all cores.

      REMARK 1: A lot of this needs to be simplified, at the end of the
        day, not a lot of people would actually know about this stuff

- (3) Every instruction that can read or write will do so respecting the
      hierarchy, so accesses to L1 are done 3 times as much as accesses to
      L2, and accesses to L3 are done sparingly and at certain stages to
      avoid stalls.

- (4) The image below shows the distribution of writes to the scratchpad,
      it's divided up into three sections with the far left being L1,
      middle left being L2, and the entire right being L3. Each red pixel
      represents 8 bytes being overwritten.
*/
