- (2) The most common example is 0.1 + 0.2 != 0.3. This sets a lot of people
      off because this is just not what you should be expecting at all.
      Numbers are numbers, so why are floats just lying here?

- (3) The easiest way to explain this is just that a floating point numbers
      make a tradeoff between performance and ease of use, over actually
      representing the numbers they represent.

      The floating point standard IEEE754 for double precision, which is what
      we care about in this presentation, uses in short, base 2 numbers in
      scientific notation. So the only numbers that you write down in your 
      programs that are strings of integer powers of 2, those are the only ones
      that can actually be exactly represented.

      REMARK 1: actually show this.... wtf

- (4) Simplifying a lot, because of maths, representing an arbitrary real 
      number
      takes an infinite amount of space. Imagine a number line, and you just
      pointed to a random number on it. If you picked that real number at 
      random, the chances that it is a number that can be represented in a 
      finite amount of space is actually zero.

      We don't have an infinite amout of memory, so representing real numbers 
      exactly is just not possible.

      IEEE754 double precision defines a 64 bit wide floating point number, so 
      there is only less than 2^64 possible numbers compared to the infinite 
      amount of real numbers. For simplicity, and because RandomX doesn't need 
      it, we don't consider NaN here.

- (5) We also have that the set of floating point doubles R contains positive 
      and negative infinity.

