/*
- (1) So, this algorithm does exist, it's called TwoSum. TwoSum is among many others
      algorithms called error free transforms. Error free transforms is basically
      just an algorithm that performs an operation, and returns the rounded value
      and the error such that the mathematically (so in the real numbers) if you 
      were to add the rounded value and the error it would be equal to the true 
      value.

      This is our RN*.

- (2) Like last slide, instead of RN* we're just going to put TwoSum here, and we're
      done! Now, this is a real algorithm, subtraction and additition on floating
      point numbers is something we can actually compute.

      But, if you don't believe me, this is the actual C code that does this.
- (3) There are no hands behind my back, this is an actual implementation of this,
      and is very similar to what RandomX.js uses.

      <explain>. Nextafter is a function in math.h that basically gets the next
      representable float in the "direction" of the second operand. So, it basically
      computes c - ulp for us.

      Now, the most important thing to check on this slide is that this is
      efficient? The question you're asking is, how could this be faster? Right?

      You're counting 1, 2, ..., different floating point operations, and a branch,
      those must be much slower than using a single add and letting hardware do the
      rounding for us.
      
      And you're right, it is slower, but not by a lot, and the alternative is much 
      much worse.
*/
#slide(title: [(4.FP) TwoSum (error free transform)])[
  #grid(columns: (5fr, 8fr), gutter: 5em, gh[    
    #uncoverb(1)[
      ```c
      // RN*(x + y)
      TwoSum(x, y) {
        s  = RN(a + b)
        a’ = RN(s - b)
        b’ = RN(s - a’)
        δa = RN(a - a’)
        δb = RN(b - b’)
        ε  = RN(δa + δb)
        return (s, ε)
      }


      ```
    ]
    #uncoverb(2)[
      ```c
      fadd_1(x, y) {
        sum, ε = TwoSum(x, y)

        if ε < 0 {
          return sum - ulp
        } else {
          return sum
        }
      }
      ```
    ]
  ], gh[
    #uncoverb(3)[
      ```c
      #include <math.h> // for nextafter()

      double sum_residue(double a, double b, double c) {
          double delta_a = a - (c - b);
          double delta_b = b - (c - a);
          double res = delta_a + delta_b;
          return res;
      }

      // return RD(a + b)
      double fadd_1(double a, double b) {
          double c = a + b;
          double res = sum_residue(a, b, c);
          if (res < 0) {
              // c - ulp
              return nextafter(c, -INFINITY);
          } else {
              return c;
          }
      }
      ```
    ]
  ])
  
]

