- (5) This allows RandomX to be fast!

      Given RandomX's preconditions, no NaNs, no infinities, no subnormals, and so 
      on, they kind of shot themselves in the foot here if they wanted to actually
      kill web mining. This goes to show, that it's actually still possible!

      Hypothetically, if RandomX allowed subnormals, you could just kill all of these
      slides on floating point before me, and RandomX.js just straight up wouldn't 
      exist. Now, though, I hope they don't get any ideas from what I just said.
*/
#slide(title: [(4.FP) In short])[
  #list[RandomX "forces" nontrivial FP rounding on you to maximise die space on an ASIC.]

  #uncoverb(2)[
    - WASM, JS, Rust, Python, etc only have access to $RN$, what now?
  ]
  

  #uncoverb(3)[
    #l-m-hr()

    - Error free transforms allow you to impl. $RD$, $RU$, $RZ$ in terms of $RN$,
      without using slow software impl.

    - This speeds up emulation of addition considerably, multiplcation, not so much.

      #l-m-meta[(EFTs still win!)]
  ]


  #uncoverb(4)[
    #l-m-hr()

    - The bane of slow software implementations is unpredictable branches, even adding
      15x more FP operations barely slow it down.

      #l-m-meta[(the cost of multiple FP operations $<$ cost of a single unpredictable branch)]
  ]

